		<item>
		<title>Advanced Problem 8</title>
		<link>http://2013-2014.hhsprogramming.com/advanced-problem-8/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 28 Jan 2014 07:34:23 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Riku Miyao]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Challenge Problems]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://hhsprogramming.com/?p=484</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Palindromes are numbers that read the same forwards as backwards. The number 12321 is a typical palindrome. Given a number base B (2 &#60;= B &#60;= 20 base 10), print all the integers N (1 &#60;= N &#60;= 300 base 10) such that the square of N is palindromic when expressed in base B; also [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Palindromes are numbers that read the same forwards as backwards. The number 12321 is a typical palindrome.</p>
<p>Given a number base B (2 &lt;= B &lt;= 20 base 10), print all the integers N (1 &lt;= N &lt;= 300 base 10) such that the square of N is palindromic when expressed in base B; also print the value of that palindromic square. Use the letters &#8216;A&#8217;, &#8216;B&#8217;, and so on to represent the digits 10, 11, and so on.</p>
<p>Print both the number and its square in base B.</p>
<h3>INPUT FORMAT</h3>
<p>A single line with B, the base (specified in base 10).</p>
<h3>SAMPLE INPUT</h3>
<pre>10</pre>
<h3>OUTPUT FORMAT</h3>
<p>Lines with two integers represented in base B. The first integer is the number whose square is palindromic; the second integer is the square itself.</p>
<h3>SAMPLE OUTPUT</h3>
<pre>1 1
2 4
3 9
11 121
22 484
26 676
101 10201
111 12321
121 14641
202 40804
212 44944
264 69696</pre>
]]></content:encoded>
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Beginner Problem 8</title>
		<link>http://2013-2014.hhsprogramming.com/beginner-problem-8/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 25 Jan 2014 22:15:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Vikram Idury]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Challenge Problems]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://hhsprogramming.com/?p=478</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[California Tools was satisfied with your work, but do not get too excited yet! Turns out that they want both the GCD feature and a LCM feature. They figure that since you are good with programming, you can easily code the LCM feature. Seems like they will not give you your paycheck until you have [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>California Tools was satisfied with your work, but do not get too excited yet! Turns out that they want both the GCD feature and a LCM feature. They figure that since you are good with programming, you can easily code the LCM feature. Seems like they will not give you your paycheck until you have done this task as well. Of course, that is hardly a problem for an ambitious worker like you.</p>
<p>The LCM of two numbers is the lowest number that can be divided by both numbers, without a remainder. The LCM of 12 and 9, for example, is 36. It is possible for the LCM to be one of the two numbers.</p>
<p><strong>Hint: </strong><strong>You may find the solution to the GCD problem (Beginner Problem 7) helpful for this problem.</strong></p>
<h3>Input Format</h3>
<p>Line 1: Two space-separated integers, lower number first</p>
<h3>Output Format</h3>
<p>Line 1: The LCM of the integers</p>
<h3>Assumptions:</h3>
<p>Both integers will be between 0 and 1,000,000</p>
<h3>Sample Input 1:</h3>
<p>16 24</p>
<h3>Sample Output 1:</h3>
<p>48</p>
<h3>Sample Input 2:</h3>
<p>3 9</p>
<h3>Sample Output 2:</h3>
<p>9</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			</item>
